<p><a href="#sdfootnote5anc" name="sdfootnote5sym">5</a> Altogether 717 people took part in all the round tables and “sub-tables,” including 55 women. The power of symbols is such that we usually only remember those who discussed at the main table. Cf. the material of Video Studio Gdańsk from 1989 (“The Role of Women at the Round Table”): <a href="https://ninateka.pl/film/rola-kobiet-przy-okraglym-stole" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://ninateka.pl/film/rola-kobiet-przy-okraglym-stole</a> (accessed November 4, 2019).</p>
<p><a href="#sdfootnote6anc" name="sdfootnote6sym">6</a> In this context, it is worth recalling a similar genealogical project, the film <em>Siłaczki</em> [<em>Strongwomen</em>]<em> </em>(2018) by Marta Dzido and Piotr Śliwiński, about Polish suffragettes of the late 19th and early 20th centuries.</p>
